content.description: Best and most logical line on the wall. Climb the technical, vertical lower section of Save Your Lunch Money, pass the anchors, then launch up the overhanging upper section. The crux is holding on between big moves on big holds.
A bit techy down low to big holds with sporty bolting the whole way. Anchors up and left of the last bolt.
content.location: To the left of the left-slanting crack system.

content.description: Climb a slightly dirty section to a stance below a roof. Pull on through this section on large interesting holds and then head up a shallow but  juggy crack that leads to a large flake. Continue straight up to the anchors. Named after the elusive ringtail because the route started off pretty dirty but eventually revealed itself to be the fun moderate it is today.
content.location: About 100 ft to the left of the other routes on the Up and Down Wall. It is just before a large gully. Find a path along the base of the cliff and you should see the bolts.

content.description: Rightmost bolted route on Up And Down Wall.  Book calls it .10d, felt more like low 5.11.  2 cruxes, one in the middle and one up high.  Excellent rock and climbing.

This is basically an easier variation to "Save Your Lunch Money II" that requires some gear.  The first half ("Filoplume", 5.10-) can also be done on it's own by finishing at anchors to the far left.

Clip first bolt of My Up And Down Life, head left through leaning dihedral with mixed gear/bolts, then bust straight out the overhanging face/arete. Good holds up high, crux is hanging on near the end. The climbing on the bottom portion is forgettable, the upper part is really good though.
content.location: Middle route on Up And Down Wall.
